"learn.topic.foundations.title" = "Court Foundations";
"learn.topic.foundations.summary" = "Understand how the regu is arranged, where pressure starts, and why touch discipline shapes the sport.";
"learn.topic.foundations.p1" = "A standard regu uses three players and a compact court that demands immediate spatial awareness. Unlike mainstream net sports with more margin for recovery, Takraw compresses time and decision-making into a few fast contacts.";
"learn.topic.foundations.p2" = "The first learning leap is understanding how the service circle, front lanes, and net pressure relate to one another. Once a player sees the geometry, rallies stop looking chaotic and start feeling patterned.";
"learn.topic.foundations.p3" = "For product design, this is the section that turns a curious newcomer into someone who can follow a point intelligently. It is not only about memorizing rules, but about seeing why each rule exists.";
"learn.topic.foundations.b1" = "Three contacts are precious, so every touch must either stabilize or create an advantage.";
"learn.topic.foundations.b2" = "Court shape matters because tiny position changes can open or close an attacking lane.";
"learn.topic.foundations.b3" = "The service phase already contains tactical intent, not just a way to start play.";
"learn.topic.roles.title" = "Role Architecture";
"learn.topic.roles.summary" = "Break down Tekong, Feeder, and Killer as a coordinated system rather than three isolated labels.";
"learn.topic.roles.p1" = "The Tekong is more than a server. This role controls emotional tempo, opening pressure, and often the confidence of the whole unit. A stable Tekong changes how the opposition receives and builds.";
"learn.topic.roles.p2" = "The Feeder is the converter. This player turns unstable touches into attackable structure, making them the cognitive hub of a regu. When spectators finally understand the Feeder, the sport becomes dramatically easier to read.";
"learn.topic.roles.p3" = "The Killer is the finisher, but the finish only works because the first two roles manufacture timing and height. This makes Takraw a highly interdependent sport, which is exactly why a role-based content hub is valuable.";
"learn.topic.roles.b1" = "Tekong sets the tone and often defines the quality of the rally's opening frame.";
"learn.topic.roles.b2" = "Feeder is the playmaking brain that restores order under pressure.";
"learn.topic.roles.b3" = "Killer turns structure into spectacle, but only after the sequence is prepared.";
"learn.topic.matchiq.title" = "Match IQ";
"learn.topic.matchiq.summary" = "Read tendencies, recover shape, and understand when elite teams choose control over highlight risk.";
"learn.topic.matchiq.p1" = "Takraw looks explosive, but elite decision-making is often conservative at the right moment. Strong teams know when to reset a pattern, when to delay, and when to attack the exposed lane instead of forcing a miracle finish.";
"learn.topic.matchiq.p2" = "This is where the app becomes more than a static encyclopedia. Match IQ content teaches users how pressure travels through a rally and how smart players buy time for rotation, spacing, and another cleaner attacking window.";
"learn.topic.matchiq.p3" = "If a user can identify why a delayed setup or safe recycle is the best move, they have crossed from passive viewer into tactical reader. That is the core retention value of the trainer plus learn-hub relationship.";
"learn.topic.matchiq.b1" = "Not every strong play is aggressive; many elite plays are stabilizing choices.";
"learn.topic.matchiq.b2" = "Reading body shape and tendency can reveal the next lane before contact happens.";
"learn.topic.matchiq.b3" = "Resetting structure is often a high-level decision, not a timid one.";
"history.explore.header" = "Tap into full cultural stories";
"history.detail.keypoints" = "Key historical takeaways";
"history.story.origins.title" = "Origins and Shared Heritage";
"history.story.origins.summary" = "Follow how kick-based court play evolved into one of Southeast Asia's most distinctive modern sports.";
"history.story.origins.p1" = "Before Takraw was formalized for modern competition, different forms of foot-based ball play already existed across royal compounds, villages, and community gatherings. The sport grew from a lived regional tradition rather than a single invented moment.";
"history.story.origins.p2" = "What makes the origin story compelling is its blend of ritual, skill display, and social play. The woven rattan ball, compact court logic, and communal setting all shaped how the sport would eventually feel on a competitive stage.";
"history.story.origins.p3" = "For a global audience, this history matters because it gives the sport identity beyond highlight clips. Understanding origin adds emotional depth and positions MelB Takraw Lab as a culture-first product, not just a rules app.";
"history.story.origins.b1" = "Early Takraw-like play was rooted in shared regional practice, not a single modern league system.";
"history.story.origins.b2" = "Material culture, especially the woven ball, remains part of the sport's visual identity.";
"history.story.origins.b3" = "History gives context that helps new audiences care more deeply.";
"history.story.regional.title" = "Regional Power and National Identity";
"history.story.regional.summary" = "See how Thailand, Malaysia, and neighboring countries helped turn Takraw into a visible modern discipline.";
"history.story.regional.p1" = "Thailand became one of the strongest contemporary homes of Takraw through visibility, repetition, and cultural confidence. The sport gained legitimacy not only through winning, but through public familiarity and institutional support.";
"history.story.regional.p2" = "Malaysia also played a defining role in shaping organized formats and sustaining one of the sport's most committed audiences. Across the region, Takraw became part of how athletic grace, control, and identity were expressed publicly.";
"history.story.regional.p3" = "This regional concentration is strategically important for the app. It means the product can be niche globally while still resonating deeply in the places where Takraw is already meaningful.";
"history.story.regional.b1" = "Regional strength gave the sport continuity before global digital storytelling caught up.";
"history.story.regional.b2" = "National identity and local pride helped sustain audience attention.";
"history.story.regional.b3" = "A multilingual product can bridge existing strongholds and new discovery markets.";
"history.story.modern.title" = "The Modern Spectacle Gap";
"history.story.modern.summary" = "Takraw now has world-class visual drama, but still lacks enough premium digital products that explain it well.";
"history.story.modern.p1" = "Modern broadcast and social media make Takraw instantly striking. Acrobatics, impossible saves, and sharp timing create clips that grab attention even from people who have never heard of the sport.";
"history.story.modern.p2" = "The problem is conversion. Spectacle alone does not teach the viewer what just happened or why a decision was smart. That gap between visual excitement and true understanding is where MelB Takraw Lab fits naturally.";
"history.story.modern.p3" = "By combining images, article-style content, and an intuitive trainer, the app can become an onboarding layer for the sport itself. This is a stronger position than chasing generic scores or mainstream-stat products.";
"history.story.modern.b1" = "Takraw already wins attention visually, but still needs interpretation tools.";
"history.story.modern.b2" = "Education and spectacle work best together when the UI guides the eye.";
"history.story.modern.b3" = "A niche sport product becomes valuable when it teaches context, not only facts.";
